# Suggested Readings

Note: Readings with an asterisk in front of them are ones we have read and enjoyed.

*Golbeck, AL, I Olkin, and YR Gel (Eds.) (2016) Leadership and Women in Statistics. Boca Raton, FL: CRC Press.
Note: Chapter 2: Persuasion, Presence, and Patience: Important Characteristics of Women in Leadership was good and generated an interesting discussion 

*Hariharan, Janani (2019). "I felt lost in a new academic culture. Then I learned about the hidden curriculum." ScienceMag. doi:10.1126/science.caredit.aay0523
http://sciencemag.org/careers/2019/05/i-felt-lost-new-academic-culture-then-i-learned-about-hidden-curriculum#

*Hewlett, Sylvia Ann (2013). Forget a Mentor, Find a Sponsor: The New Way to Fast-Track Your Career. Cambridge, MA: Harvard Business Press.

Hogan, Kevin (1999). Talk Your Way to the Top: Communication Secrets to Change Your Life. Gretna, LA: Pelican Publishing Company.

*Huston, Therese (2017). How Women Decide. Boston, MA: Houghton Mifflin Harcourt.

Kaeppel, K, RS Grenier, and E Bjorngard-Basayne (2020), "The F Word: The Role of Women's Friendships in Navigating the Gendered Workplace of Academia," Human 
Resource Development Review 19(4), 362-383. DOI: 10.1177/1534484320962256

Lerner, Helene (2015). The Confidence Myth: Why Women undervalue their skills, and how to get over it. Oakland, California : Berrett-Koehler Publishers, Inc.

*Mohr, Tara (????). 10 Rules for Brilliant Women. (Free workbook: https://www.taramohr.com/10-rules/)

*Mohr, Tara (2015). Playing Big: Practical Wisdom for Women Who Want to Speak Up, Create, and Lead. New York, NY: Avery.

*Mohr, Tara (2014). Why Women Don’t Apply for Jobs Unless They’re 100% Qualified
https://hbr.org/2014/08/why-women-dont-apply-for-jobs-unless-theyre-100-qualified

Monarth, Harrison (2009). Executive Presence: The Art of Commanding Respect Like a CEO. New York, NY: McGraw-Hill.

Stephens, Suzanna M.W. (2009). The Big Book of Self Promotion. New York, NY: Harper Design.

*Yang, Y, NV Chawla, and B Uzzi (2019). "A network’s gender composition and communication pattern predict women’s leadership success." PNAS.
https://www.pnas.org/content/early/2019/01/14/1721438116 
